    lesson: 'This is the Schelling insight inside Putnam\'s model: a credibly small win-set ("I literally cannot get this ratified below $X") shifts the burden of concession onto the other side, because you have a believable reason you cannot move. The catch is symmetric risk — if both sides\' win-sets are too small to overlap, the deal dies. Tying your hands is powerful only when the overlap survives.',
